# 1\) Analogy to AlphaGo, AlphaZero, & MuZero

AlphaGo \[[3](https://www.nature.com/articles/nature16961)\], AlphaZero \[[4](https://arxiv.org/abs/1712.01815)\], and MuZero \[[5](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-020-03051-4)\] systems were a watershed moment for reinforcement learning and AI. They demonstrated the power of RL when done right, and many assumed AGI would follow just by generalizing these systems from board games to the real world. Well, nine years after AlphaGo, that moment might be finally coming.

First, let‚Äôs do a quick recap of the three systems with respect to the knowledge they started with:

|  | Knowledge they started with |
| :---- | :---- |
| AlphaGo | Human expert data. |
| AlphaZero | Rules of the game. |
| MuZero | No rules provided. |

If we were to draw analogies (which are very imperfect), DeepSeek-R1 (and OpenAI O1) feel like they are partly on their way to AlphaGo. They are not fully AlphaGo level yet as there were still no ‚Äúmove 37‚Äù like moments. DeepSeek-R1‚Äôs training strategy \- with a complicated pipeline of cold-start data followed by RL \- somewhat mirrors how AlphaGo was built with multiple neural networks and SFT on the policy network.

Just as AlphaZero outperformed AlphaGo by simplifying its architecture and training process, I hypothesize that further simplification and scaling of reinforcement learning could lead to significant advancements beyond models like R1. Instead of relying on supervised fine-tuning, we could potentially encode desired behaviors directly within the reward signal, allowing the model to learn more effectively through self-play. This aligns with advice from ‚ÄúThe Bitter Lesson‚Äù \[[6](https://www.cs.utexas.edu/~eunsol/courses/data/bitter_lesson.pdf)\], which states that the simpler process without much human intervention always wins. Learning and search is all you need\! It‚Äôs like Occam‚Äôs razor for training pipelines.

Just as advancements from AlphaGo to AlphaZero to MuZero produced even more powerful superhuman agents for board games, a similar approach and techniques may produce superhuman agents in other domains like math and coding.

## Self-play & The Data Wall

Some predicted that LLM performance would stall due to all the data being used up. I never bought this argument for two reasons. First, even though all the textual data may have been used up, we are still scratching the surface when it comes to data from other modalities. This includes visual data like videos, audio data, and sensory data from robotics. Second, I believe we will be able to get *more* out of the data that we do have by having better algorithms and training procedures. This is because a human consumes orders of magnitude less data than an LLM and is still smarter and more useful (as of Feb 2025).

Now, I have a third reason to say why we likely won't hit a data wall. With the same techniques as used in AlphaZero, where rapid improvement was made via self-play. The recent success of DeepSeek-R1 provides strong evidence that LLMs can similarly leverage self-play to generate their own training data and achieve significant advancements.

Gemini 2.0 generation models having the ability to use tools natively may also mean that future models will just use Google Search to get information rather than it being baked in during pre-training.

# 2\) Generalization to other domains

DeepSeek-R1‚Äôs RL training was done using math and LeetCode problems data. This, of course, makes sense as it‚Äôs relatively easy to 1\) obtain data and 2\) give a clear reward in these domains. This still leaves an important open question: will the strong reasoning performance in math and LeetCode generalize to other domains? That is, will we see the same level of performance in other domains (like physics or biology) that were not used during RL training? If we do see the same level of performance generalize to other domains that would be amazing. It means we would not need to painfully collect data in every single domain.

However, it‚Äôs likely that such performance won‚Äôt carry over to other domains that the model was not explicitly trained on. We can see hints at this in the OpenAI O1 report, where performance in domains like physics was less pronounced than the improvement in math.

This then, leaves us with the question of how we can obtain data for RL training in other domains? Unlike math and LeetCode, not all problems have a clear \+1, \-1 reward. For example, we may build a superhuman agent for LeetCode due to there being a clear reward signal, but how can we build a superhuman end-to-end software engineer where the reward signal is less clear.

It may also be the case that we may not need a lot of data in other domains. The s1 paper \[[7](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2501.19393)\] shows that only a 1000 examples is good enough to almost reach O1-level performance. Maybe we can do RL training in math and coding where we have lots of data and then do RL training in other domains with orders of magnitude less data as the model does not need to learn that it needs to reason or the basic principles of reasoning from scratch. This is like curriculum learning.

# 3\) Hierarchical Planning

I have been playing around with Gemini 2.0 Flash Thinking Experimental 01-21 (what a mouthful) extensively. It‚Äôs my favorite chatbot. But I think it has deficiencies in a couple of areas that if cleared will lead us to very powerful AI. The first being hierarchical planning and the second being spatial reasoning. We will discuss the latter in the next takeaway.

The classic example of hierarchical planning is planning a flight from New York to Paris. Humans plan that trip hierarchically. First, they think about booking the flights. Then they think about packing. Then they think about getting a cab, and so on and so forth. Hierarchical planning is missing from current-generation reasoning models, that is, planning at different levels of abstraction as needed.

I witnessed this failure mode when I asked Gemini Thinking Flash to replicate a memory optimization code change. Even though it was a simple 33 line code change that involved making a vector\<unique\_ptr\<object\>\> to a vector\<object\> and cleaning up the destructor, the model failed. Looking at the reasoning traces, it‚Äôs clear that the model is messing up because it is ‚Äúthinking‚Äù at different levels of abstraction all at once and therefore ended up being confused on what to do. It was ‚Äúthinking‚Äù about the high level objective of memory optimization, the lower level tasks like rewriting the function, the even lower level tasks of the vector increments, and the error it was seeing all *at the same time in the same paragraph*. This is analogous to a human thinking about what muscles to move when planning a trip to Paris.

If the reasoning model was able to think hierarchically. Carefully plan at the higher level of abstraction, and then move to the lower ones as necessary. Then these models could be deployed to a wider range of applications.

There‚Äôs evidence that humans have different segments of the brain taking charge of different levels of abstraction \[[8](https://books.google.ca/books/about/A_Brief_History_of_Intelligence.html?id=tymCEA)\]. With the prefrontal cortex doing the more high level planning, and then passing on info to the motor cortex which does more low level planning like which muscles to move. Sutton & Barto also state something similar in \[[9](http://incompleteideas.net/book/the-book-2nd.html)\] when they say ‚ÄúTemporal Abstractions via Options‚Äù is one of the open frontiers in RL.

There is an open question of whether hierarchical planning emerges organically by just scaling up RL. If so, that would be great. Otherwise new algorithms and breakthroughs would be needed to patch up this important pillar.

# 4\) World Models

The second missing piece in current generation reasoning models is spatial reasoning. Gemini Thinking Flash solved pretty easily all the most challenging calculus problems I have done (I am not too sure if that says a lot about the model‚Äôs ability or my abilities üòê). But it failed pretty spectacularly when I gave it a simple task of vectorizing a convolutional kernel.

The problem is rather straightforward: ‚Äú*We want to vectorize the convolution kernel to be a single matrix multiplication instead of having to use a for-loop. Given a 3x3 single channel image, consider ‚Äòflattenting‚Äô it to be a 9-dimensional vector **x**.  Consider a stride-4 convolution layer, with zero padding size of 2 and let the output be **y**. A) Work out the dimensions of the column-vector y. B) Give the matrix **A** such that y=Ax‚Äù.* I did prompt tuning and gave hints to the model.

Working out this problem requires drawing up the 3x3 image matrix, sliding the convolutional kernel across the image, and then recording the necessary values of the kernel in the matrix A. (See the appendix for the solution). The model correctly got the answer for one row of matrix A, but failed for the rest as that requires successfully sliding the kernel 4 strides, which it could not do. The key property of this problem is that it requires *spatial reasoning*. As a human, I solved this by mentally simulating the sliding convolutional kernel and then doing it on paper.

The fact the Gemini Thinking Flash failed at this problem is revealing. It demonstrates that these models lack spatial awareness. It adds weight to the argument that learning about gravity through actions and experience like a human baby does is different from learning about gravity by passively observing a lot of text that talk about it.

I hypothesize that one solution to this problem would be connecting these reasoning models with world models \[[10](https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/sima-generalist-ai-agent-for-3d-virtual-environments/), [11](https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/genie-2-a-large-scale-foundation-world-model/), [12](https://nvidianews.nvidia.com/news/nvidia-launches-cosmos-world-foundation-model-platform-to-accelerate-physical-ai-development)\] so they can simulate their reasoning using the world model when required. Thus, investing and scaling up world models may be a key step on the path to AGI.

Another potential solution would be if these models can experience the real world, possibly through embodied AI.

# 5\) Search & Creativity

It‚Äôs pretty clear that RL will eat our lunch when applied domains with clear rewards. But that begs the question about domains where there is no clear reward; we have touched on this in takeaway 2 above. Another area to think about is questions where even humans don‚Äôt have the answers. How can we provide a reward for such questions? Well, this is where search comes in. ‚ÄúMove 37‚Äù by AlphaGo was true creativity, and it came about due to search. Whatever the answer ends up being, incorporating search in these models will make them very powerful, and useful. It will be the beginning of ‚Äúmove 37‚Äù like moments in all other domains. Soon everyone will truly experience how Lee Sedol felt 9 years ago.

# 6\) Reasoning in Latent Space

Reasoning in token space is incredibly useful as it allows us to interpret and debug the model‚Äôs ‚Äúthinking‚Äù. However, reasoning in latent space should be more powerful and expressive due to the flexibility provided by continuous regimes. In addition, it should also be more latency and compute efficient. Will we need another Transformer-esque breakthrough to have an architecture that does this or will slight modifications to the Transformer help us get this ability?

The safety concern with latent-space reasoning is that we lose the ability to monitor the model‚Äôs ‚Äúthinking‚Äù. I guess that makes them more human-like.
